Lorraine, France":"Bar-le-Duc, Meuse, Lorraine, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bourgogne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile.","Americanized form of French   Bourgoin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bourgoin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphee, Alyre, Andre, Armand, Aurore, Celina, Emile, Gilberte, Jacques, Laurent, Lucienne, Olivier.","French:","variant of <b>Bourgouin</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), a habitational name for someone from Burgundy (Old French <i>Bourgogne</i>), a region of eastern France having Dijon as its center. The area was invaded by the <i>Burgundii</i>, an ancient Germanic tribe from whom it takes its name, in about  AD  480. The duchy of Burgundy, created in 877 by Charles II, King of the Western Franks, was extremely powerful in the later Middle Ages, especially under Philip the Bold (1342–1404; duke from 1363). Compare   Bourgoyne   and   Bourguignon  ."]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Marie Bourgogne Countess of Bar was born in 1298. She married Édouard de Bar, Count of Bar on 11 February 1310, in Montbard, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1336, at the age of 38, and was buried in Bar-le-Duc, Meuse, Lorraine, France."},"et"